**`PipelinePositionAfter` godoc contradicts the actual pipeline ordering**

The pipeline is built as `[before] [base] [after] [app]`, so `PipelinePositionAfter` places middleware *after the base filters but still before the terminal application*. The current godoc — "inserts middleware after the application" — says the exact opposite of what happens. `PipelinePositionBefore` is also slightly imprecise ("before the application" rather than "before the base filters"), but the `After` case is the more confusing one since the app is always last.

```suggestion
	// PipelinePositionBefore inserts middleware before the base filters in the pipeline.
	PipelinePositionBefore PipelinePosition = "before"
	// PipelinePositionAfter inserts middleware after the base filters but before
	// the terminal application in the pipeline.
	PipelinePositionAfter PipelinePosition = "after"
```

**`mw.Config` can silently overwrite the `paste.filter_factory` entry**

The filter section map is initialized with `"paste.filter_factory": mw.FilterFactory` and then immediately overlaid with the contents of `mw.Config`. If a caller includes `"paste.filter_factory"` in `mw.Config` (accidentally or not), the value set from the dedicated `FilterFactory` field is silently overwritten and the INI output will contain the wrong factory entry.

Consider either guarding against this key in `mw.Config`, or documenting clearly in godoc that `Config` must not contain `"paste.filter_factory"`:

```go
filterConfig := map[string]string{
    "paste.filter_factory": mw.FilterFactory,
}
for k, v := range mw.Config {
    if k == "paste.filter_factory" {
        continue // FilterFactory field takes precedence
    }
    filterConfig[k] = v
}
```
